  "text": "The Android Activity lifecycle is implemented across four key Java source files in the android-frameworks-base repository:\n\n1. **Activity.java** (core/java/android/app/Activity.java): This is the base class `public class Activity extends ContextThemeWrapper` that applications extend to create user-facing screens. It defines the core lifecycle methods (onCreate, onStart, onResume, onPause, onStop, onDestroy) that developers override to manage activity state transitions.\n\n2. **ActivityThread.java** (core/java/android/app/ActivityThread.java): This is the main thread class `public final class ActivityThread extends ClientTransactionHandler` that runs in each Android application process. It drives lifecycle transitions by processing lifecycle items and calling the appropriate callbacks on Activity instances through client transactions.\n\n3. **ActivityRecord.java** (services/core/java/com/android/server/wm/ActivityRecord.java): This is the server-side representation `final class ActivityRecord extends WindowToken` that the system service maintains for each running activity. It tracks activity state on the system server side and manages the lifecycle state from a system perspective.\n\n4. **ActivityTaskManagerService.java** (services/core/java/com/android/server/wm/ActivityTaskManagerService.java): This is the system service `public class ActivityTaskManagerService extends IActivityTaskManager.Stub` that manages activity stacks and tasks across the entire system. It coordinates activity lifecycle transitions and enforces system-wide activity management policies.\n\nThese four components work together: ActivityTaskManagerService orchestrates lifecycle state changes on the system side, communicating via ActivityRecord; ActivityThread executes lifecycle transitions in the app process; and Activity provides the developer-facing API for responding to these lifecycle events."
}

